== An Experiment With Time
_by J.W. Dunne_

#hm-note[
  Dunne's work provides a "scientific" framework for understanding the non-linear nature of the astral body. In the TTAO curriculum, this is used to train the student's perception of "Time-Shifted" data—recognizing that the dreaming mind often observes future events as easily as past ones.
]

=== The Theory of Serialism
- *The Multi-Dimensional Observer:* To observe a 3D world moving through time (4th dimension), the observer must exist in a 5th dimension. This implies an infinite series of "observers" and "times."
- *The Absolute Time:* The "Golden Thread" that exists outside the successive layers of serial time.

=== The Nature of Dreams
#doctrine[
  "The dreaming mind is not restricted to the present moment, but wanders freely along the timeline of the individual's experience, viewing past and future as a unified landscape."
]

- *The Blend:* Dreams are a mixture of past memories and future "pre-presentations."
- *The Effect:* Most people forget precognitive dreams because they do not fit the linear "cause-and-effect" narrative of the waking mind.

#inner-work[
  *The Dunne Technique (Dream Tracking):*
  1. *Immediate Recording:* Keep a notebook and pencil under the pillow. Record every detail immediately upon waking, before any other thought intervenes.
  2. *The Reverse Search:* Every evening, read the dream notes from *previous* nights and compare them with the events of the current day.
  3. *Identification:* Look for "identifying marks"—specific, unusual details that appeared in a dream and later manifested in physical reality. This confirms the astral body's ability to transcend linear time.
]
